      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6fa3219bd6b29de0",
      "text": "In many fields we are trained from a young age to share only when our thoughts are considered finished enough for public presentation. This starts in school, and continues in our professional lives. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "85d49a143da77a52",
      "text": "There are many social, scientific and personal benefits to sharing early. \"Release early, release often\" is a mantra in open source software. Lean startups and agile development emphasise the importance of discovering mistakes early and adapting fast. But this is still far from mainstream practice."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d6775b4f8b942464",
      "text": "In scientific practice, we are penalised by the system of [[First Past The Post Publishing]], and it is standard practice in many field now to only present research that has actually been published at conferences for fear of others copying and publishing methodology or results before that all important paper is accepted for publication."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2188de5e4e9a9aeb",
      "text": "In Fedwiki [[Writing with Strangers]] is not a familiar or a comfortable task. It is a challenge even if it soon becomes an addictive one. Experience working with groups, in school, or with experienced adults demonstrates the need to slowly and gently encourage the practice of writing together."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cdbf2bcd7d54d804",
      "text": "One way to cushion this fear is to [[Publish To Your Peers]], in a form of publishing we call an [[Open Secret]]. In this form of publishing anyone who knows the address can turn up and contribute, but the address (the [[URI]]) is not advertised publicly. This is not how it works on the internet, this is not compatible with the power of global search."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
